  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Imprisonment\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences for more complex cases\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundered funds\n- May include bank accounts, real estate, vehicles, and other property\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Civil penalties\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Frequency of offenses\n- Whether the laundering involved other criminal activities\n- Individual's role in the laundering scheme\n\nThe primary federal statute governing money laundering is 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956, which details specific offenses and corresponding penalties.\n\nNote: These are general guidelines, and actual sentencing can vary based on specific case circumstances and judicial discretion.",
